>As a FP developer who knows little of PB, I'd be interested in what you've
>learned on the PB newsgroup that has dampened your enthusiasm?

>I think others would be interested too.

>Thanks.  Ed.

The PB folks seem to be getting a lot of GPFs and are registering
general disappointment with ver 4.0 for not being a stunning improvement
over 3.0, is more like a 3.1 (but requires more system resources so
runs more slowly for a lot of people).

I also find the PB seems to have limited native string handling functions.
Doesn't have the equivalent of FP's AT("pattern",string), or STUFF(), or
SUBSTR().  Has just things like LEFT(), RIGHT() and "pattern"$string.
I'd hate to have to build FOR...ENDFOR loops to duplicate AT() using
just LEFT().

Apparently there's a Funckey add-on to PB with lots of prewritten code
that helps a lot.  PB folk who've responded directly say they hardly
if ever have to go to C++ to write external routines.

My fear remains that PB is mostly a front end screen generator with 
datawindows kinda like the FP BROWSE, and is not designed to do much
crunching between the screen and the SQL server attached to the back
end.

On the other hand, I expect PB's custom drivers for Sybase, Oracle etc,
which are not ODBC, are faster than MS ODBC.  And as far as FP2.x goes,
PB is way better at working with servers (the FP Connectivity Kit was a
disappointment in my experience) and is already fully object oriented.

That's about all I have to say.  PB folks don't seem to know much about
FoxPro and vice versa, so I'm still waiting for that balanced, objective
article.  Maybe DataBased Advisor will run a piece, once FP3 is released.

Kirby

